column168: DUE TO THE INCREASED ELEVATION NECESSARY TO CROSS LOVELAND PASS (11,999 FT) THE BOILING TEMPERATURE OF THIS PRODUCT WAS REDUCED TO A POINT WHERE THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO BOIL INSIDE THE TANK TRAILER. OUR ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED TO CLEAN UP THE PRODUCT THAT LEAKED OUT AND ANY CONTAMINATED SOIL. ANY TRAILER INVOLVED IN A HM SPILL IS TO BE EMPTIED AND PLACED IN THE YARD WITH THE DOOR OPEN SO THE FUMES CAN DISSIPATE.

OUR DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING AT THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION.  HE WAS ON TOP OF OUR TRAILER WATCHING THE PRODUCT TO INSURE THAT THE COMPARTMENT WOULD NOT OVERFLOW.  HE TOLD THE LOADER TO SHUT DOWN, WHICH HE DID, BUT THEN PURGED HIS LINE WITH NITROGEN.   THIS CAUSED A SURGE OF PRESSURE IN THE TRAILER CREATING A SLIGHT OVERFLOW.

column168: DURING A ROUTINE TIRE CHECK AT MIDWAY TRUCK STOP, OUR DRIVER DISCOVERED THE PROBLEM WHILE IN ROUTE FROM BASHVILLE, TN AT GREER, SC.  OUR DRIVER REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO OUR CENTRAL DISPACTH.  THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE BILL OF LADING WAS CALLED.  AFTERWARDS, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EMS WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  AN ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS APPLIED TO MATERIAL AND UNIT MOVED TO A SAFER LOCATION ON TRUCK STOP LOT.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS IDENTIFIED AND FOUND TO BE EMPTY.  A CREW FROM OUR ASHEVILLE, NC SERVICE CENTER, ALONG WITH A CREW  FROM TIMCO, ARRIVED AND REMOVED THE DRUM, INCLUDING THE DAMAGED DRUM (CONTAINED IN SALVAGE DRUM) AND PLACED ON TIMCO TRUCK FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION TO INMAN, SC.  A SMALL AREA WAS OBSEVED IN THE PARKING LOT THAT SHOWED LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS. HOWEVER, THIS DRIED WITHIN A FEW HOURS.  THE FIRE MARSHALL WAS SATISFIED WITH THE CLEAN UP OF AREA, AS WELL AS TRUCK STOP PWNER.  IT APPEARS THAT MOST OF THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER, WHICH HAD ABSORBENT MATERIAL REMOVED AND WAS ALLOWED TO DRY BEFORE BEING MOVED FOR CLEAN UP. TO PREVENT FUTURE PROBLEMS OF THIS NATURE, WE WILL CONTINUE TO EDUCATE OUR EMPLOYEES ON THE IMPORTANCE OF CHECKING AND HANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: WHILE TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF HAZARDOUS WASTE AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FROM BALTIMORE, MD. TO SOUTH CAROLINA, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE HAD A BLOW-OUT ON THE INNER SIDE WALL OF THE FRONT LEFT TIRE.  THE VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING IN THE RIGHT HAND LAND ON I-95 IN VIRGINIA WHEN THE TIRE BLEW.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A COLLISION WITH MOVING VEHICLES ON HIS LEFT, THE DRIVER STEERED RIGHT TOWARD A LANE UNDERGOING REPAIRS.  ONCE THE DRIVER GOT THE VEHICLE GOING TO THE RIGHT HE COULD NOT STRAIGHTEN IT OUT AGAIN.  HE WENT INTO THE CLOSED LAND ON HIS RIGHT AND HIT A SMALL UNOCCUPIED VA. HIGHWAY DEPT. DUMP TRUCK THERE FOR THE ROAD MAINTENANCE.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER PULLED THE DUMP TRUCK FORWARD AND TO THE RIGHT UNTIL THE DUMP TRUCK WAS JAMMED INTO THE JERSEY WALL.  THE IMPACT OF THE DUMP TRUCK HITTING THE JERSEY WALL CAUSED THE TRACTOR TRAILER TO JACK-KNIFE.  THIS JAMMED THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRACTOR INTO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER.  THE COLLISION WITH THE DUMP TRUCK AND THE TRACTOR OPENED THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND PUNCTURED SIX (6) DRUMS.  FOUR OF THE DRUMS CONTAINED PETROLEUM OILS, ONE (1) CONTAINED SODIUM HYDROXIDE DRY AND THE OTHER EITHER CONTAINED DRY SODIUM HYDROXIDE OR DRY SOLID DETERGENT.  ALL DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE OVERPACKED AND ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PUT INTO DRUMS.  THE ELEVEN (11) DRUMS CONTAINING THE SPILL CLEAN-UP WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT THE GSX SERVICES OF SOUTH CAROLINA LANDFILL IN PINEWOOD, SC.  THE OTHER DRUMS ON MANIFEST C1303 WILL ALSO BE SHIPPED TO GSX AS PREVIOUSLY CONSIGNED.  A COPY OF THE ORIGINAL MANIFEST IN INCLUDED.

A GEORGIA-PACIFIC CHEMICAL TRUCK CARRYING SULFURIC ACID SPILLED A SMALL PORTION OF ITS LOAD FRIDAY MORNING ON ITS WAY TO BELLINGHAM FROM ANACORTES.  THE SPILL WAS OBSERVED BY A MOTORIST ON STATE STREET ABOUT 9 AM AS THE TRUCK APPROACHED ITS DESTINATION, G-P'S LOCAL PULP AND PAPER OPERATIONS. COMPANY OFFICIALS NOTIFIED BELLINGHAM FIRE DEPARTMENT AND QUICKLY DELIVERED AN ALKALINE POWDER TO THE SCENE TO NEUTRAZLIE THE ACID PRIOR TO WASHDOWN BY FIREMEN.  QUANTITY OF THE SPILL IS UNKNOWN BUT THOUGHT TO BE LESS THAN 75 GALLONS.  A LOOSE HATCH ON TOP OF THE TRUCK WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE LEAK, COMPANY OFFICIALS SAID.  WASHDOWN ACTIVITIES REQUIRED CLOSURE OF STATE STREET, NEW YORK TO MAPLE FOR SEVERAL HOURS. ALTHOUGH NO PROPERTY DAMAGE WAS REPORTED, BELLINGHAM FIRE DEPARTMENT DID RECEIVE ONE RESPIRATORY COMPLAINT CALL FROM THE CORNER OF STATE AND HOLLY STREETS.  DILUTION OF THE MATERIAL BY G-P AND FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL REMOVED ANY HAZARD CAUSED BY THE SPILL.  HARMLESS SALT FROM THE WASHDOWN WAS NOT EXPECT TO HAVE ANY EFFECT ON THE ENVIRONMENT. NECESSARY STEPS (IF ANY) TO PROTECT FISH AT NEARBY MARINE HERITAGE PARK WERE CARRIED OUT FOLLOWING NOTIFICATION OF THAT FACILITY. SULFURIC ACID IS A COMMON INDUSTRIAL CHEMICAL USED FOR A VARIETY OF NEEDS THROUGHOUT THE WORLD.  G-P USED THE CHEMICAL FOR PULP BLEACHING AND AS A DRYING AGENT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HOURS, SATURDAY, MAY 25, 1991, EMPLOYEES AT THE CONRAIL BIG FOUR RAIL YARD IN AVON IN., OBSERVED PRODUCT NEAR THE TOP MANWAY OF TANK CAR ACFX-87947.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM SHIPPER (JONES HAMILTON) ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION OF THE CAR AT 1830 HOURS AND FOUND A TORN MANWAY GASKET WHICH WAS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  GASKET WAS REPLACED AND CAR WAS CLEARED TO DESTINATION AT 1930 HOURS, MAY 25, 1991.

PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO DAMAGE CONTROL BY SUPERVISOR.  UPON INSPECTION IT WAS FOUND TO BE EMPTY OF CONTENTS DUE TO LEAKING CAP.  DISPOSED OF BOTTLE IN ACCORDANCE WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL GUIDELINES.

PACKAGE FOUND IN UNLOAD.  TAKEN TO CLEANUP AND DAMAGE COUNTER.  INSPECTION SHOWED SMALL PUNCTURE IN UPPER HALF OF GALLON OF PLASTIC JUGS.  THE LOST CONTENTS WAS ABOUT 1 QUART.  BALANCE WAS POURED INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  REMAINS WERE DISPOSED IN ACCORDANCE TO HAZ. MAT REGULATIONS.
PACKAGE WAS LEAKING ON DELIVERY VEHICLE, EVENTUALLY THE FUMES EFFECTED THE DRIVER.

THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING WHILE LOADING AND WAS TAKEN TO THE REWRAP AREA.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE INNER PACKAGING WAS INSUFFICIENT BECAUSE THERE WERE NO CLIPS ON THE CAN.  THE PACKAGING AND THE LIQUID WERE ABSORBED WITH SOLUSORB, DOUBLE BAGGED AND PLACED IN A DUMPSTER.  THE ENTIRE AMOUNT WAS LOST.

PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO SERVICE CENTER AT 7:00 PM.  PACKAGE WAS LEAKING A VERY LITTLE ON TOP.  OPEN PACKAGE FOUND COVER WAS DENTED AND LEAKING. LIQUID ON CARTON WAS NEUTRALIZED. THE PARCEL WAS REPACKED PER DOT SPECIFICATIONS AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

DRIVER NOTICED AN ODOR ESCAPING FROM THIS VEHICLE AND CHECKED THE LOAD TO FIND ONE CARTON LEAKING.  THE FREIGHT WAS CONSULTED AND CLEANUP WAS DRUM AND THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT DELIVERED TO THE SOMSIGNEE.

WHILE TRAILER WAS BEING UNLOADED, ONE CARTON FELL FROM THE TOP AND HIT THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, CAUSING ONE INNER BOTTLE TO BREAK.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY PAIL.  THE UNDAMAGED CONTENTS WERE RECOUPED INTO A DRY CARTON AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: THE STAPLES USED TO CLOSE THE BOTTOM OF THE CARTON APPARENTLY MADE A PINHOLE PUNCTURE IN THE BOTTOM OF INNER CONTAINER DURING TRANSIT.  A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED AND WAS COMPLETELY ABSORBED BY THE CARTON.  THE CARTON WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY PAIL AND IS BEING HELD FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE UNDAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED.

PRESSURE WAS APPARENTLY BUILT UP INSIDE THE DRUM DURING TRANSIT AND CAUSED MATERIAL TO RELEASE THROUGH THE PRESSURE/VENTILATION BUNG.  THE DRUMS WERE ISOLATED ON THE DOCK AND THEN PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM FOR FORWARDING TO CONSIGNEE.

DRIVER. BOTH EMPLOYEES GOT UNDER SHOWER IMMEDIATELY AND RINSED DOWN.

column168: TRAILER BEGAN LEAKING ENROUTE.  THE TRAILER RUBBER LINING HAD DETERIORATED IN ONE SMALL AREA ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO CORRODE THE OUTER SHELL.  THE AREA AFFECTED WAS EXTREMELY SMALL (ABOUT THE SIZE OF A NAIL) THEREFORE THE SPILL WAS MINOR.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND ALL NECESSARY REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.
WHEN DISCONNECTING HOSE AT TRAILER AFTER UNLOADING DRIVER SPILLED APPROXIATELY 3 GALLONS OF RESIDUAL PRODUCT ON PLANT DRIVEWAY.  SPILL PANS WILL BE PROVIDED ON FUTURE DELIVERS.

column168: UNIT WAS SOUTHBOUND ON US23 NEAR BRIGHTON, MI.  ROAD HAD SLIGHT CURVE TO RIGHT.  UNIT WENT OFF ROAD TO THE LEFT INTO MEDIUM AND ROLLED OVER. PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF PRESSURE VENT.  I NOTIFIED NATIONAL RESPONSE, INCIDENT #73292-1, MICHIGAN DEPT. OF NATURAL RESOURCES AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND MICHIGAN STATE POLICE.
55 GALLONS BROKE OPEN ON BOTTOM DURING TRANSIT APPARENTLY METAL FATIGUE.

DURING PRE-TRIP CLEAN-OUT WAS IN PLACE ON TANK.  ACCORDING TO LOADER, CAP WAS IN PLACE WHEN LOADING WAS COMPLETED.  GUARD AT SHIPPER NOTICED SOME MOISTURE WHEN TRUCK WAS EXITING PLANT.  TRUCK WAS STOPPED IMMEDIATELY. SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY.  CAUSE WAS FOUND TO BE MISSING CLEAN-OUT CAP.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRACTOR-TRAILER PROCEEDING NORTH ON RT. 601.  WEATHER WAS HAZY WITH A MISTING RAIN.  STOPPED AT RAILROAD TRACKS AT WHICH TIME THE WARNING LIGHTS WERE BLINKING.  THE LIGHTS THEN STOPPED BLINKING, THEN STARTED AGAIN.  THE DRIVER LOOKED BOTH WAYS AND SAW NO TRAIN, HOWEVER HE DID SEE WHAT HE BELIEVED TO BE A CREW WORKING ON THE TRACKS.  BELIEVEING THE CREW HAD SOMETHING TO DO WITH THE LIGHTS, THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO CROSS THE TRACKS. WHEN NEARLY COMPLETELY ACROSS THE TRACKS, THE DRIVER HEARD THE TRAIN HORN BLAST, WITH IMPACT ALMOST IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING. THE TRAIN PUT A HOLE APPROXIMATELY 4 INCHES IN THE BACK END OF THE TRAILER WITH THE IMPACT CAUSING THE TRACTOR-TRAILER TO ROLL ON ITS SIDE.  SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY HANDLED BY S.C. DHEC AND AREA EMERGENCY CREWS.  OHM CORPORATION, A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR, WAS BROUGHT IN BY CARRIER TO HANDLE THE CLEAN-UP.
ONE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE DRUM WAS REPAIRED AT OUR TERMINAL.  ABSORBENT AND THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO MOBAY.

column168: SIX, ONE GALLON PAILS WERE DAMAGED DURING UNLOADING AT TERMINAL.  THE SIX PAILS AND THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A POLYLINED DRUM WHICH WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND THEN WAS FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

THREE METAL CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED DUE TO POOR LOADING.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED UN CLEANING THE AREA.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS PLACED IN A PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED RECOVERY DRUM AND WAS THEN FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

column168: DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO OFF LOAD PRODUCT WITH THE USE OF AIR PRESUURE. A SHORT TIME AFTER THE AIR PRESURE WAS APPLIED, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS NOT FLOWING INTO THE CUSTOMERS STORAGE TANK.  WHILE TRYING TO DETERMINE THE REASON FOR THE PRODUCT NOT FLOWING, DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT HAD BEGAN TO DRIP FROM THE CLAMP HOLDING THE EXTERNAL VALVE IN PLACE. WHEN HE ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE CALM, IT CAME APART ALLOWING THE EXTERNAL VALVE TO SEPARATE FROM THE TANK .  THIS ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO FLOW UNDER PRESSURE UNTIL ANOTHER DRIVER WHO HAD SEEN WHAT HAPPENED WAS ABLE TO CLOSE THE INTERNAL VALVE ONT HE TANK.  ALTHOUGH DRIVER THAT WAS ATTEMPTING TO TIGHTEN THE CLAMP DID GET THE PRODUCT ON HIM, HE WAS ABLE TO WASH IT OFF IN AN EMERGENCY SHOWER BEFORE BEING INJURED AN ANY WAY. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND NEUTRALIZED BY PLANT PERSONNEL.  TOTAL CLEAN UP HAS NOT BEEN COMPLETED AS OF THIS DATE. BECAUSE THE CLEANUP HAD NOT BEEN COMPLETED, THE TOTAL COST FOR THE PRODUCT LOSS AND CLEANUP HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS LOADED IN WINONA, TX. ON 5-29-91.  THE DRIVER LEFT WINONA HEADING FOR CHANUTE KS.  HE DROVE 2 1/2 HOURS AND STOPPED AT THE OK. TOLL PLAZA WERE HE SLEPT FOR 8 HOURS.  HE THEN CONTINUED ON FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 1/2 HOURS MORE WHICH IS WHEN THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED.  HE STATED HE DOESN'T THINK HE FELL ASLEEP BUT DOESN'T KNOW  WHAT HAPPENED EITHER.  THE FIRST THING ABOUT THE ACCIDENT HE REMEMBERS IS THE RIGHT FRONT WHEEL GOING OFF THE PAVEMENT ONTO A SOFT SHOULDER.  HE TRIED TO RECOVER BUT FELT THE TRUCK & TRAILER GOING OVER.  THE TRUCK & TRAILER CAME TO REST ON ITS RIGHT SIDE IN THE DITCH.  SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICES WAS DISPATCHED AND ON THE SCENE WITHIN 1 HOUR FROM THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT.  MIKE CLOONEN FROM COAL CITY COB CO. ARRIVED AT THE SCENE APPROXIMATELY 5 1/2 HOURS AFTER THE ACCIDENT AND STAYED AT THE SCENE UNTIL THE CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETE.  ALL OF THE PROPER AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED EITHER FROM THE SCENE OR FROM OUR TX. OFFICE.  THE TRUCK & TRAILER HAVE BEEN COMPLETELY GONE OVER AND NO DEFECTS WERE FOUND.  THE DRIVER VOLUNTARILY RETIRED AFTER THE ACCIDENT.  HE IS 62 YEARS OLD AND DECIDED IT WAS TIME.  THE ONLY EXPLANATION THAT MAKES ANY SENSE AT ALL IS HE FELL ASLEEP.  AS FOR ACTION TO PREVENT FURTHER ACCIDENTS WE HOLD REGULAR MEETINGS WITH ALL OF OUR DRIVERS AND HAVE TOLD ALL OF THEM TIME & TIME AGAIN THAT IF THEY GET TIRED PULL OVER AND SLEEP NO MATTER HOW MUCH SLEEP THAY HAVE HAD!  WE WOULD MUCH RATHER HAVE THEM GET TO THE DESTINATION LATE THAN NOT AT ALL.  SINCE THE ACCIDENT I HAVE ONCE AGAIN EMPHASIZED THIS POINT.

column168: AIRCRAFT TOO LATE IN MEM TO MAKE SORT.  OUTER PACKAGING WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED OR CERTIFIED AS CONTAINING DANGEROUS GOODS.  TWENTY-EIGHT PIECES OF FREIGHT WITH ATLANTA-AREA DESTINATIONS WERE TAKEN TO THE DELTA CARGO OFFICE.  PRIOR TO LOADING, THE PACKAGE WAS NOT ICED TO BE LEAKING.  SPOKE WITH TIM FURR AT DELTA; THEY WERE NOT ABLE TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL. I WNET TO DELTA TO CLEAN-UP PAINT.  (DOCUMENTS FROM DELTA ARE INCLUDED). NOTIFEID FAA OFFICE IN NASHVILLE, LEFT DETAILED MESSAGE ON RECORDER LATER OBTAINED EXPEDITING LOGS TO ATTEMPT TO IDENTIFY BOTH SHIPPER AND RECIPIENT.  REQUESTED COPY OF AIRBILL; MICROFILM COPY RECEIVED ON 6-19-91. PACKAGE IS HELD IN HUB PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION

LOAD OF FAK, DRUMS ON FLOOR WITH FIBREBOARD BOXES OF LEATHER ON TOP. FOUND LEAKING DRUM IN RIGHT ROW THIRD STACK FROM REAR.  DRUM HAD CRACK IN LOWER ROLLING HOOP CAUSED BY LOADING OR PRELOADING MISHANDLING.  AREA WAS GOUGED DEEPLY AT FAILURE LOCATION.  DRUM WAS PATCHED AND RETURNED TO LOAD FOR LOCAL DELIVERY WHERE ENTIRE LOAD WILL BE OFF LOADED AND CONTAINER CLEANED.  LIQUID ON FLOOR WAS COVERED BY ABSORBENT WHICH WAS LEFT IN CONTAINER.  THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE ON GROUND WHERE CONTAINER HAD BEEN PARKED.

column168: DRIVER OF PETROLEUM EXPRESS TRANSPORT HOOKED UP HOSE TO TRANSPORT AND BEGAN UNLOADING PRODUCT PRIOR TO HOOKING HOSE TO FILL PIPE ON TANK. APPROXIMATELY 450 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ON THE GROUND BEFORE THE DRIVER REALIZED HIS ERROR.  WITHIN 1 HOUR WE HAD THE PRODUCT ON TOP OF THE GROUND SOAKED UP WITH ABSORBANT PADS & PILLOWES & BOOMS.  WE THEN HAD THE CONTAMIANTED SOIL REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH FRESH DIRT.  THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED.  WE THEN HAD A MEETING WITH ALL OTHER DRIVER TO DISCUSS THE INCIDENT, HOW TO PREVENT IT,AND THE CONSEQUENCES.

DRIVER NOTICED MATERIAL LEAKING ENROUTE TO DESTINATION AND NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR.  THE TRAILER WAS PARTIALLY UNLOADED TO LOCATE THE SOURCE OF LEAKAGE.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WRE LOCATED AND THE MATERIAL IDENTIFIED.  THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED AND ALL SPILLAGE CLEANED.

METAL ROD LOADED ADJAENT TO CARTON PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE LID, CAUSING A VAPOR LEAK.  THE DRIVER NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR AND THE SHIPMENT WAS UNLOADED.  THE DAMAGED CAN WAS SEALED INSIDE A RECOVERY PAIL FOR DISPOSITION.
LIQUID FROM GLASS BOTTLE LEAKED THRU PACKAGE AND FUMES WERE INHALED BY DRIVER.  PACKAGE WAS GOOD.

column168: WHILE PACKAGE CAR DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO SHURE BROS. OF WHEELING, IL., HE OPENED UP REAR DOOR AND HEARD A HISSING SOUND.  HE THEN STARTED CLEARING AWAY THE CARTONS AND NOTICED A LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BOX.  AT THAT POINT THE DRIVER NOTICED A DIFFERENCE IN THE AIR QUALITY AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR.  THE CENTER MANAGEMENT TEAM CONTACTED THE EMERGENCY CONTACT TELEPHONE NUMBER 1-800-535-5053 (INFOTRNC) WHICH ADVISED US TO NOTIFY THE WHEELING FIRE DEPT.  THE FIRE DEPT. NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLAGE AND AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE TOOK BOTH OUR DRIVER AND 1 SHURE BROS. EMPLOYEE TO THE HOSPITAL.  BOTH WERE TREATED AND RELEASED.

TANK CAR GATX 99404, LOAD OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S., UN 1993, WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BETWEEN THE OPERATING ROD AND PACKING GLAND OF THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE LEAKING APPARENTLY OCCURRED ONLY WHEN THE CAR WAS STRATED OR STOPPED THE LIQUID SURGED INSIDE THE TANK.  THE LEAKAGE WAS MINIMAL AND ONLY CREATED A WET SPOT ON TOP OF HTE TANK CAR. GALESBURG DIVISION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONDERS STOPPED THE LEAK BY REMOVING THE PACKING GLAND, ADDING PACKING MATERIAL, AND REPLACING THE PACKING GLAND PRIOR TO RELEASING THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.
TRAILER WAS APPARENTLY SITTING SLIGHTLY BELOW THE DOCK WHEN THE FORKLIFT SLID DOWN THE RAMP, STRIKING TWO 5 GALLONS PAILS AND ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE RESIN SOLUTION TO ESCAPE.

column168: HIGHWAY INSPECTION REVEALED SMALL DRIP FROM DISCHARGE VALVE.
END OF HOSE CAME OFF WHILE DRIVER WAS PUMPING OFF THROUGH THE CONSIGNEE HOSE.  THE CONSIGNEE PUT STAY DRY ON THE SPILLED PRODUCT, THEN PLACED IT IN DISPOSAL DRUMS.

OUR DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO DESTINATION WHEN HE WAS STOPPED BY A TN PSC OFFICER ADVISING HIM THAT THERE WERE FUMES COMING FROM TOP OF HIS TRAILER. THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND WERE ABLE TO CONTROL THE FUMES ENOUGH TO ALLOW OUR VEHICLE TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION WITH AN ESCORT.  AFTER UNLOADING THE TRAILER WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS FOUND THAT THE LINING IN THE DOME HAD CRACKED ALLOWING THE FUMES TO ESCAPE.  THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR REPAIR.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DURING A ROUTINE REST STOP IN TRANSIT, OUR DRIVER RETURNED TO HIS VEHICLE, AFTER MAKING A CHECK CALL, TO FIND SOME MATERIAL LEAKING OUT OF THE REAR DRAIN HOLES OF THE TRAILER.  HE NOTIFIED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES WHO HELPED HIM SECURE THE AREA AROUND THE TRUCK.  WE THEN CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED A LOCAL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR TO TRAVEL TO THE SCENE TO REMEDIATE THE PROBLEM. IT WAS FOUND THAT ONE DRUM, LOADED ON A PALLET AT THE REAR MOST PART OF THE TRAILER, HAD BROKEN THROUGH THE PALLET AND A PIECE OF WOOD HAD PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED, THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND COLLECTED.  THE OVERPACK WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE AND THE WASTE DRUMS WERE SHIPPED BACK TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSAL.
column172: Reusable molded polyethylene container without overpack RHNA*

column168: THE RAMP AREA WAS RESTRICTED FOR ACCESS.  LOAD WAS OPENED & CHECKED BY CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL USING LEVEL B PERSONAL PROTECTION EQUIPMENT.  LEAK WAS LOCATED IN THE LEFT FRONT AREA.  RAILCAR & GROUND SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED & THE TRAILER WAS DERAMPED ONTO PLASTIC SHEETING.  4 DRUMS WERE PLACED ON 48 X 48 PALLETS & WERE SECURED WITH 3 PLASTIC STRAPS. PALLETS WERE SHRINKWRAPPED.  THE ONLY BRACING CONSISTED OF 1 2X4 BOARD NAILED ACROSS REAR OF LOAD WHICH WAS INTACT.  LOAD HAD NOT MOVED.  ALL PALLETS WERE WET FROM THE LEAKING PRODUCT.  THE PALLETS WERE UNLOADED ONTO PLASTIC SHEETING.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS LOCATED ON THE 2ND STACK LEFT ROW. WE DID NOT HAVE THE OPPORTUNITY TO CLOSELY EXAMINE THIS DRUM BECAUSE IT WAS PROMPTLY OVERPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  IT HAD NO INDICATIONS OF ABUSE.  IT SEEMED THAT LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE LOWER CHIME.  DUE TO NATURE OF PRODUCT WE DID NOT REMOVE IT FROM RECOVERY DRUM FOR CLOSER EXAMINATION. THE FLOOR IN TRAILER KBSZ 230035 WAS NEUTRALIZED.  THE LOAD WAS LATER TRANSLOADED INTO XTRZ 752171.  EXTERIOR OF DRUMS WERE NEUTRALIZED & DISPOSAL OF ALL PALLETS.  KBSZ CAR WAS PRESSURE BLASTED.

DRIVER STATED HE FAILED TO CLOSE OUTLET VALUE ON #3 COMPARTMENT ALL THE WAY AFTER UNLOADING HIS PREVIOUS DELIVERY.  WHEN HE REMOVED DUST CAP TO UNLAOD THIS LOAD PRODUCT WENT ONTO UNLOADING AREA, PAVED, APPRO 5-6 GALLONS DRIVER USED HIS SPILL CLEAN UP KIT OF PADS TO CLEAN SPILL UP.

column168: WE WERE DELIVERING GASOLINE INTO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS AT A MINI-MART. AN AUTOMOBILE DROVER OVER OUR PRODUCT HOSE AND DROP GUN WHICH CAUSED THE SPILL.  DRIVER OF THE AUTOMOBILE FLED THE SCENE BUT WAS LATER APPREHENDED. FIRE DEPARTMENT ABSORBED GASOLINE WITH CHEM-OIL-A-WAY, SPREAD A EMULSIFIER AND WASHED DOWN.  WE ARE DISPOSING OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE THROUGH CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT.  CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT IS EXPECTED TO PICK UP THE WASTE WITHIN THE NEXT 30 DAYS.

column168: PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED NONDECLARED (SEE AWB# 6655351990) AS SUCH WAS LOADED AS REGULAR FREIGHT.  IN TRANSIT THE TOP CLOSURE WAS LOOSENED AND DURING TRANSFER THE TOP CAME OFF 1 GALLON.  THE RAMP NOTIFIED DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION AND DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER. MSDS'S FROM THE SHIPMENT SHOWED THE MATERIAL TO BE PAINT WITH A FLASHPOINT OF 23 DEGREES F.  THE FAA WAS THEN NOTIFIED.  THIS NOTIFICATION WAS MISFILED AND THIS CAUSED THE DELAY IN REPORTING TO THE FAA.  THE RAMP NOTIFIED ME IN A TIMELY FASHION.

DURING INSPECTION CARMAN SMELLED AMMONIA NEXT TO UTLX 38756, THE SOO LINE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE COORDINATOR, WAS NOTIFIED, WHO RESPONDED TO THE CAR AND FOUND VERY SLIGHT HISSING SOUND COMING FROM THE LIQUID LINE VALVE.  THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED 1/2 TURN, AND THE HISSING SOUND STOPPED COMPLETELY.  AFTER REPAIRS, THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON TO BILLED DESTINATION.  NO CLEAN UP WAS NECESSARY IN CONNECTION WITH THIS INCIDENT.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING GASOLINE AT "ON YOUR WAY" IN CHESTER, MN THE DRIVER HAD A TANK FILL UP AND 10 GALLONS SPILLED ON THE GROUND IN THE AREA OF THE FILL PIPE.  THE AREA WAS CLEANED UP WITH FLOOR DRY.

THE DRIVER HAD NOT NOTICED ANYTHING UNUSUAL UNTIL THE OFFICER MAKING THE INSPECTION SAW SOMETHING LEAKING FROM BACK OF TRAILER AS DRIVER STARTED TO LEAVE REST AREA.  THE PROPER ATHORITIES, (ENVIRONMENTAL SYSTEMS AND THE U.S. ARMY AND CIVIL DEFENSE AGENCY) WERE CALLED PER THE INVESTIGATING OFFICER AND THE DRIVER WAS NOT ALLOWED IN OR AROUND THE TRAILER, SO AS A CONSEQUENCE WE DO NOT KNOW FIRST HAND WHAT REALLY CAUSED THE CONTAINERS TO SPILL.  ALL WE CAN GO BY IS THE REPORTS GIVEN TO US AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL, AS THE SHIPPER OR THE CONSIGNEE WILL NOT RETURN OUR TELEPHONE CALLS OR CORRESPOND WITH US ON ANY OF THESE MATTERS.  WE HAVE TURNED THE MATTER OVER TO OUR ATTORNEY FOR FURTHER ACTION.

column168: THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS BLOWN IN TRANSPORTATION.  A VERY MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED, IN KIND, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

SUTTLES'S DRIVER LOADED  AT NIACET CORP. LOCATED IN NIAGARA FALLS, NEW YORK. WHEN LOADED FINISHED LOADING 45820 POUND OF MONOCHLOROACETIC ACID, OUR DRIVER QUESTIONED IF ALL FITTINGS WERE TIGHT.  LOADER SAID YES AND SUTTLES' DRIVER LEFT LOADING SITE.  DRIVER STOPPED AT TRUCK STOP LOCATED ON I-90 AND US 6.  WHILE CHECKING HIS UNIT, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT FRONT CLEAN OUT FLANGE WAS LOOSE AND LEAKING.  DRIVER CALLED CHEMTREC AT 1-800-424-9300 REPORTED SPILL TO THEM.  DRIVER CALLED SAFETY DEPARTMENT AT SUTTLES AND IN TURN DON WARTICK CALLED CHEM TREC AND SPOKE TO RICHARD STEVENS WHICH PUT CALL THROUGH TO NIACET AND SPOKE TO MR.  ROBERT HOPPER, WHO WENT TO SITE AND CLEANED UP PRODUCT AND TOOK CLEAN UP MATERIAL BACK TO THEIR PLANT FOR DISPOSAL.

column58: Cylinder Neck or Shoulder; Cylinder Sidewall - Other
column168: STANDARD WELDER'S TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS HEADED EAST BOUND ON 1-55 HEADED TO BLYTHEVILLE, ARKANSAS. OUR DRIVER T.L. TAYLOR LOOKED BACK AFTER HITTING THE FAMOUS BUMP AT THE 7TH STREET OVERPASS, AND MOTICED A FIRE COMING FROM THE SIDE OF THE ROAD WHERE HE HAD JUST PASSED.  T.L. CALLED PLANT OPERATIONS ANDTOLD WILLIAM EZZELL THAT HE WAS PULLING OVER TO INVESTIGATE. I TOLD HIM TO DO SO, LET ME KNOW WHAT IT WAS AND CALL ME AS SOON AS HE COULD.  I SENT THE ACETYLENE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY TO THE SCENE AND CALLED THE WET MEMPHIS FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE FIRE SEPARTMENT STATED THAT THEY WERE ON THE SCENE AND WOULD WAIT UNTIL MY SUPERVISOR ARRIVED BEFORE ATEMPTING TO PUT OUT THE FIRE.  CHUCK BRITTON (ACETYLENE SUPERVISOR) ARRIVED ON THE SCENE, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT LET HIM TAKE CHARGE.  HE REPORTED THAT (2) B ( 40 CUBIC FEET ACETYLENE CYLINDERS) HAD FALLEN OFF OUR TRAILERAND ON STRICKING THE PAVEMENT, THE VALVE SHEARED OFF.  THE GAS IN THE TWO CYLINDERS INGNITED AND WAS BURNING  OVER NEXT TO THE GUARDRAIL. CHUCK WAS CARRYING A FIRE EXTINGUISHER APPROVED FOR THIS TYPE OF FIRE AND EXTINGUISHED THEM.  AFTER THE FIRE WAS OUT CHUCK AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT GATHERED UP THE CYLINDER, CHECKING TO BE SURE THE NUMBER ON THE GROUND, MATCHED THE MANIFEST AND LOADED THEM INTO A SERVICE TRUCK.  THE FIRE CHIEF SAID HE DIDN'T KNOW WHY THE DOT PEOPLE HADN'T ARRIVED BUT RELEASED OUR TRAILER AND SUPERVISOR TO LEAVE THE SCENE.  THE TRACTOR TRAILER AND SERVICE TRUCK WERE ROUTED BACK TO THE PLANT, WHERE A NEW LOAD OF CYLINDERS WERE LOADED AND THE TRUCK WAS RE-DISPATCHED TO BLYTHEVILLE, ARKANSAS.  THE CYLINDERS INVOLVED HAVE BEEN QUARANTINED FOR A SAFETY INSPECTION AND THE CYLINDERS WILL BE SCRAPED PENDING INSEPCTION.  THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS; 1.  THOSE TYPE CYLINDERS ARE SMALL AND WERE NOT TIED DOWN SUFFICIENTLY TO WITHSTAND THAT TYPE OF BUMP CROSSING THAT OVERPASS. 2. EVEN THOUGH THE SPEED AT THAT STRETCH HAD BEEN REDUCED TO 45 MPH WE HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVERS TO REDUCE BELOW 40 MPH UNTIL THE CONSSTRUCTION HAD FIXED THESE BUMPS.  3.  IT IS POLICY WHEN GOING THROUGH THIS AREA (WHICH HAS BEEB UBDER REPAIR FOR TWO YEARS) TO PULL OVER AT THE SCALED (AFTER WEIGHING AND RETIGHTEN OUR LOADS.  WE ARE APPROXIMATELY ONE MILE FROM THERE WHEN THE CYLINDERS WERE BUMPED OFF.  4.  WE'VE STARTED TO SECURE HESE TYPE CYLINDERS IN A METAL CONTAINER AS OF 5/10/91 FOR MORE SECURE TRANSPORTATION.  ANY QUESTIONS INVOLVING THE INCIDENT OR THIS REPORT, PLEASE CALL 901-728-4787 AND TALK WITH WILLIAM EZZELL, PLANT MANAGER.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: ON MAY 8, 1991, AROUND 2:30 P.M. OUR DRIVER, HILLARD SAUNDERS WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON I-10 CLOSE TO BALDWIN, FLORIDA, WHEN HE NOTICED A CLOUD OF DUST BEHIND HIS TRAILER, AND THE TRAILER WAS IN A PARTIAL RAISED POSITION.  THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH RQ HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID N.O.S., ORM-E, NA9189, (EMISSION CONTROL DUST/SLUDGE FROM THE PRIMERY PRODUCTION OF STEEL IN ELECTRIC FURNACE) (K061) (D006, D008)ERG. #31.  THE MATERIAL ORIGINATED FROM FLORIDA STEEL CORPORATION, P.O. BOX 518, BALDWIN, FLORIDA 32234 AND WAS BEING TRANSPORTED TO HORSEHEAD RESOURCES DEVELOPMENT COMPANY, EAST PLANT, DELAWARE AVENUE, PALMERTON, PA 10871.  APPROXIMATELY 28,060 LBS SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY AND GROUND.  THE STATE POLICE WERE ONTHE SCENE.  O.H MATERIAL AND ANDERSON COLUMBIA ENVIRONMENTAL WERE CALLED TO DO THE CLEAN-UP.  VACUUM TRUCKS WERE USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE REPORT NUMBER IS 71277.
column172: Highway hopper trailer for solid materials only

column168: I WAS NOTIFIED CONTAINER TOLU272857 MAY BE LEAKING.  THE CONTAINER WAS IMPORTED FROM EUROPE TO HOUSTON ON OUR VESSEL, DISCHARGED AND PARKED IN THE YARD.  THERE ARE NO SHIPPING PAPERS ON AN IMPORT LOAD.  I EXTRACTED THE INFORMATION OFF OUR COMPUTER SYSTEM AND DANGEROUS CARGO MANIFEST. I CALLED THE LOCAL FREIGHT FORWARDER IN HOUSTON TO OBTAIN A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  I WAS CONTACTED BY MICHAEL RUCCELO WITH ATOCHEM AT APPROXIMATELY 10:15 AM.  HE THEN HAD ROBERT ROENWASSER AND JIM CONNALLY CONTACT ME.  I RECEIVED THE MSDS AT 11:43 AM.  THE PORT FIRE MARSHALL WAS CALLED AND HELPED TO ACCESS THE SITUATION.  I CALED MR. CONNALLY AND ADVISED THAT THEY NEEDED TO SEND THEIR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM IN TO CLEAN AND CONTAIN THE LEAK.  THE TEAMS DID NOT ARRIVE UNTIL 4 PM.  THE BAGS WERE WRAPPED IN POLYURETHANE AND SECURED TO A PALLET. THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN OVERLOADED.  WHEN THE DOORS WERE SHUT, ONE OF THE PALLETS BROKE PUNCTURING THE BAGS.  THREE QUARTERS OF THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED DUNNAGE, THEN TWO MORE PALLETS ON THE END.  THESE TWO PALLETS EXTRUDED BEYOND THE FLOOR. THIS BEING A SOLID, ONCE THIS COMMODITY IS IN CONTACT WITH AIR, IT ABSORBS MOISTURE THEREBY CAUSING A LIQUID.  THREE BAGS WERE TOTALLY DAMAGED. THREE BAGS WERE WET.  ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO THE RECOVERY DRUM; APPROXIMATELY 6 BAGS, 350 LBS.  THE TWO PALLETS WERE THEN BROKEN DOWN INTO TWO MORE PALLETS.  TWO PALLETS WERE PLACED INSIDE THE LOCAL DELIVERY TRUCK WITH RECOVERY DRUM AND WERE DELIVERED DIRECT TO BLENTECH. MR. THOMAS WILL ADVISE THE SHIPPER IN EUROPE OF LOADING PATTERN.  I ALSO ADVISED MR. CONNALLY THAT THE RESPONSE TEAMS SHOULD BE DISPATCHED MORE EXPEDITIOUSLY.  10:15 AM UNTIL 4 PM IS TOO LONG TO RESPOND TO A HAZARDOUS SPILL. THE CONTAINER WILL NEED A NEW FLOOR AND THE CONTAINER NEEDS TO BE REPAINTED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Fire, Temperature, or Heat
column168: I WAS NOTIFIED AT 1515 OF LEAKING CONTAINER.  ADVISED PORT AUTHORITY FIRE DEPARTMENT.  FIRE MARSHALL OPENED AND COULD NOT FIND PACKAGE LEAKING. CALLED ROBERT ROSEWAKER.  ATOCHEM NOTIFIED DALE BLAKE WITH ATOCHEM IN HOUSTON.  MR. BLAKE BROUGHT IN THEIR HAZARDOUS RESPONSE TEAM.  REWORKED CONTAINER, REMOVED FOUR RIPPED BAGS INTO ONE SALVAGE DRUM.  RELOADED BAGS BY HAND.  RESEALED.  COMMERCIAL CARRIER DELIVERED SALVAGE DRUM TO BLENTECH IN HOUSTON.  ATOCHEM COMPLETED REWORK AT 1930.  SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED. CONTAINER WAS IMPROPERLY LOADED.  BAGS WERE RIPPED WHEN LOADED.  TOO MANY BAGS LOADED ON DOCK PALLET.  MR. BLAKE IS CONTACTING HIS EUROPE OFFICE TO START RELOADING PROCESS.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: CHEMTREC NOTIFIED LITTLE ROCK CORRIDOR MANAGER ADVISING A REPORT HAD BEEN RECEIVED FROM MCGEHEE, ARKANSAS FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT A TANK CAR IN MCGEHEE YARDS WAS LEAKING. CAR WAS ISOLATED (PICKENS, AR. MP 432) AND SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) CLIFF HILL WAS NOTIFIED.  HIS INSPECTION DETERMINED EIGHT, THREE QUARTER (3/4) INCH BOLTS WHICH SECURED THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE TO THE MANWAY NOZZLE COVER WERE LESS THAT WRENCH TIGHT, ALLOWING VAPOR RO LEAK BETWEEN  BASE OF VALVE AND NOZZLE COVER.  LEAK WAS SECURED BY USING 3/4 INCH DRIVE AND EXTENSION TO TIGHTEN EIGHT BOLTS. "SNOOP" LEAK DETECTOR WAS APPLIED TO CHECK FOR LEAK AND LEAK HAD BEEN STOPPED.  PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS SECURED WITH PIN AND SEAL (UP S-79608). SUN REFINING (WILBER SMITH) WAS NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT BY CHEMTREC AND BY SSA/HM HILL.  SSA/HM HILL ADVISED MR. SMITH THAT CAR SHOULD BE SHOPPED FOLLOWING UNLOADING FOR INSPECTION OF SAFETY VALVE SEAT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) TOM ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED BY FRA INSPECTOR (JAMES DUNCAN) AND UP MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE (KEITH HARMISON) CONCERNING A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR AROUND TANK CAR WGFX 206.  SSA/HM ROBINSON RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED A SMALL VAPOR LEAK AT THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE. SSA/HM ROBINSON SECURED THE VAPOR LEAK BY TIGHTENING THE PACKING GLAND NUT (ABOUT 1 1/2 TURNS).  LEAK WAS STOPPED AND TANK CAR SECURED FOR MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND THE ADDIS FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED.  C.F. INDUSTRIES (ROY SAVOY) AND WILLARD GRAIN FEED (CARL MCCORMICK) WERE ALSO BRIEFED ON INCIDENT AND ACTION TAKEN.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) DON LOW WAS NOTIFIED THAT SWITCH CREW IN CHEYENNE YARDS NOTED AN AMMONIA ODOR COMING FROM THE AREA OF SOUTH TRACK ONE. SSA/HM LOW RESPONDED AND HIS INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT TANK CAR GATX 40651'S GAUGING ROD PACKING GLAND NUT WAS FINGER LOOSE.  SSA/HM LOW SECURED THE PACKING GLAND WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AWAS SEALED WITH SEAL BN-HW-465654; IT WAS RESEALED WITH UP-C-562357. SS/HM LOW CONTACTED CHEMTREC (JIM COOPER) AND MANAGER, RAIL FLEET OPERATIONS, FARMLAND INDUSTRIES (JOHN GOBLE).

column168: DISTRICT SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (DSA/HM) KEN DECHANT WAS NOTIFIED THAT UPON DE-RAMPING OF TRAILER COEZ 651478, WORKERS NOTED LIQUID RUNNING FROM UNDERSIDE OF TRAILER.  INTERIOR INSPECTION BY DSA/HM DECHANT DETERMINED TRAILER LOADED WITH 80 DRUMS OF WASTE, PAINT RELATED MATERIAL, 16 OF WHICH WERE LEAKING.  ONE DRUM LEAKING FROM BUNG, REMAINING 15 WERE LEAKING FROM THE HEAD/RING CLOSURE AREA.  THE LOAD HAD NOT BEEN BLOCKED AND BRACED EXCEPT FOR ONE PARTIAL PLYWOOD BULKHEAD AT REAR OF LOAD, WHICH WAS SECURED ONLY AT ONE END TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. UPRR MANAGER, EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (BOB STINE), BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES CHIEF INSPECTOR (AL MATY) AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES (RON PETERSON AND SIGFREDO AGUILAR) ARRIVED ON THE SCENE (05/11/91). SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES TIGHTENED ALL CLOSURES TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. TWO (2) REMOVABLE HEAD DRUMS REQUIRED RE-GASKETING.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL (200 LBS) WAS SPREAD THROUGHOUT TRAILER FLOOR TO ABSORB SPILLAGE AND TO CONTAIN ANY POTENTIAL FURTHER SPILLAGE.  ALL EXTERIOR EVIDENCE OF PREVIOUS LEAKAGE EVAPORATED PRIOR TO SHIPPERS ARRIVAL.  LOAD WAS THEN BRACED AND TRAILER RELEASED FOR HIGHWAY MOVEMENT TO FINAL DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING AND DECONTAMINATION.

column168: CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT'S VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON LOUISIANA HIGHWAY 33. AFTER CROSSING THE I-20 OVERPASS, OUR DRIVER, GEORGE DANIELS RAMP. IT WAS APPARENT THAT THE TURN WAS NEGOTIATED AT AN EXCESSIVE SPEED, THAT RESULTING IN THE VEHICLE OVERTURNING ON ITS SIDE AND THE SPILLING OF ITS CARGO.  THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 11:10 A.M. ON MAY 17.  MR. DANIELS, OUR DRIVER, IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED ME OF THE INCIDENT FROM A PAY PHONE ACROSS THE STREET.  HE TOLD ME THAT A STATE POLICE OFFICER, WHO MUST HAVE BEEN NEARBY, WAS ON THE SCENE, THE TRUCK WAS OVERTURNED, AND THAT MOST OF THE LOAD, WHICH CONSISTED OF STEEL PIPE AND METAL DEBRIS (PCB CONTAMIANTED) WAS ON THE GROUND.  I DETERMINED FROM THE DRIVER THAT THERE WAS NO IMMEDIATE THREAT TO HUMAN HEALTH OR THE ENVIRONMENT, AS HE ADVISED ME THAT THERE WERE NO LIQUIDS TO SLUDGES VISIBLE AND THE INCIDENT SITE WAS NOT NEAR A DRAIN ENTRANCE OR BODY OF WATER.  I THEN INSTURCTED MR. DANIELS TO ADVISE THE OFFICER THAT WE WOULD RESPOND TO THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY TO BEGIN CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS, AND FOR HIM TO CALL ME BACK AS I NEEDED ADDITIONAL INFORMATION FOR THE NOTIFICATION OF THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  AT APPROXIMATELY 11:17 A.M. AFTER INITIATING OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW, I NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL UNIT OF THE INCIDENT.  MR.  DANIELS CALLED ME BACK, I THEN COMPLETED CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT'S "HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL INCIDENT REPORT", WHICH IS A FILL IN THE BLANK FORM COVERING ALL THE NECESSARY INFORMATION REQUIRED TO BE REPORTED TO TEH NATINAL RESPONSE CENTER.  I NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, AS REQUIRED, REFERENCE N.R.C. REPORT 72397.  I THEN NOTIFIED TREASEA EVANS WITH ENSCO AND ADVISED HER OF THE SITUATION.   OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW CONSISTING OF: 2 WRECKERS, A TRACTOR/TRAILER END DUMP, FRONT END LOADER, AND 6 WORKERS, ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 P.M..  BILL BLANN, PRESIDENT AND OWNER OF CLEAN-UP TRANSPORT, INC., AND I RESPONSED TO ASSIST AND OVERSEE THE SITUATION.  THE ENTIRE LOAD CONSISTED OF STEEL PIPE AND METAL DEBRIS, NO LIQUIDS WERE VISIBLE OR FOUND.  THE STEEL PIPE WAS LOADED BY HAND AND THE LARGER PIECES OF METAL WERE LIFTED BY THE FRONT END LOADER AND LOWERED INTO THE WAITING END DUMP TRAILER.  ALL METAL PIPES, METAL PIECES, RUST, AND CONTAMINATED SAFETY EQUIPMENT, WERE REMOVED FROM THE SPILL SITE AND PLACED IN THE UNWRECKED DUMP TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 1,000 LBS. OF METAL REMAINED IN THE OVERTURNED DUMP TRAILER TO THE GENERATOR, ENSCO, INC., AMERICAN OIL ROAD, EL DORADO, AR., ON THE ORIGINAL MANIFEST CWMA #617163 AND SO NOTED IN SECTION 19 OF THIS MANIFEST.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL APPROXIMATELY 29,000 LBS., WAS LOADED INTO THE UNWRECKED END DUMP, REMANIFESTED AND RETURNED TO THE GENERATOR'S  FACILITY ON ARKANSAS MANIFEST AR 506884.  VERY LIGHT RAIN FELL DURING THE LATER CLEAN-UP OPERATION, BUT IT DID NOT PRODUCE ANY RUNOFF OR SPREAD ANY CONTAMINATION. AFTER COVERED WITH PLASTIC SHEETING TO PREVENT THE SPREADING OF ANY PO

column168: ANCHORAGE EMPLOYEES SUSPECTED SHIPMENT OF CONTAINING NON-DECLARED FLAMMABLE MATERIAL.  EMPLOYEES NOTIFIED DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION WHERE THEY WERE INSTRUCTED TO OPEN THE SHIPMENT FOR INSPECTION. THIS ACTION FURTHER VALIDATED OUR BELIEF THAT THE MATERIAL WAS FLAMABLE.  THE FAA IN ANCHORAGE WAS NOTIFIED AND AFTER INSPECTION BY JOHN WHITE THE SHIPMENT WAS DELARED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS BY FEDERAL EXPRESS, MARKED, LABELED, PACKAGED AND CERTIFIED AND THEN SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: ON 5/15/91 AT APPROXIMATLEY 0215 A SPILL WAS REPORTED TO ME, SHAWN HENRY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR, AIRBORNE EXPRESS, OHIO.  THE SPILL WAS LOCATED IN THE PRIMARY AREA OF THE SORT FACILITY.  UPON INITIAL APPROACH A FIBERBOARD BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID.  THE BOX WAS MARKED FORMALIN, ORM-A, UN2209. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THE BOX TO CONTAIN 150-20ML PLASTIC JARS WITH SCREW TOP CLOSURES.  EACH JAR CONTAINED A CLEAR LIQUID AND WAS MARKED "FORMALIN 10%".  THREE OF THE 150 JARS HAD LOOSENED CLOSURES WHICH IS BELIEVED TO BE THE CAUSE OF LEAKAGE.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE REPACKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND TRUCKED TO DESTINATION.  BE ADVISED THAT THERE WERE NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE LIDS.

ON 5-9-91 AT APPROXIMATLEY 0112 A SPILL WAS REPORTED TO ME, SHAWN HENRY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR, AIRBORNE EXPRESS, WILMINGTON OHIO.  THE SPILL WAS LOCATED IN A FREIGHT CONTAINER STAGED OUTSIDE OF THE FEED AREA OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  UPON INITIAL APPROACH TWO FIBERBOARD BOXES, TAPED TOGETHER, WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING A CLEAR LIQUID.  THE BOXES WERE MARKED "CONSUMER COMMODITY, OMR-D.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED EACH BOX TO CONTAIN 6 - 16OZ PLASTIC BOTTLES OF LIQUID FLAVORING.  TWO OF THE TWELVE BOTTLES AND LOOSENED CLOSURES WHICH IS BELIVED TO BE THE CAUSE OF LEAKAGE. THE INNER RECEPTACLES OF THIS SHIPMENT WERE NOT PACKAGE IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR 173.6.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE REAPCKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND TRUCKED TO ITS DESTINATION.

ON 5/14/91 AT APPROXIMATELY 0115 A SPILL WAS REPORTED TO ME, SHAWN HENRY, HAZARDOUS MATERILA COORDINATOR, AIRBORNE EXPRESS, WILMINGTON, OH.  THE SPILL WAS LOCATED IN THE PROMARY AREA OF THE SORT FACILITY. UPON INITIAL APPROACH A FIBERBOARD BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A GREEN LIQUID. FURTHER INVESTIFATION REVEALED THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A GREEN LIQUID. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THE BOX TO CONTAIN -1 LITER PLASTIC JARS WITH SCREW TOP CLOSURES AND 1-1 GALLON JUG WITH A SCREW TOP CLOSURE.  THE 1 GALLON PLASTIC JUG HAD  A LOOSENED CLOSURE WHICH IS BELIEVED TO BE THE CAUSE OF LEAKAGE.  I REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SEND A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET ON THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE MSDS INDICATED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS 1,1,1 TRICHLOROETHANE SOLUTION.  UNDER 49 CFR REGULATIONS 1,1,1 TRICHLOROETHANE SOLUTION IS ORM-A UN 2831.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD IN ILN FOR FAA INVESTIGATION. UPON RELEASE BY THE FAA THE SHIPMENT WILL BE MOVED VIA TRUCK IN A DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM.

column168: THERE WERE 7 CTNS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (HM) IN SHIPMENT.  CARTONS WERE STACKED 3 HIGH IN TRAILER.  DRIVER FAILED TO DOWNSTACK CTNS BEFORE MOVING VEHICLE FROM A DELIVERY.  WHEN HE OPENED TRAILER DOOR AT SITE OF INCIDENT, HE DISCOVERED CTNS HAD FALLEN AND LIQUID LEAKING FROM CONTAINERS.  HE ALERTED PEOPLE IN BUILDING OF SUNTEC MARINE OF HAZARD.  CHARLOTTE COUNTY FIRE & RESCUE, HM RESPONDED TO SCENE.  ONE-FOURTH (1/4) MILE AREA WAS EVACUATED.  HM TEAM ABSORBED LIQUID WITH DIRT AND PLACED INSIDE RECOVERY DRUM.  ONE PERSON, PATRICK MALACISI, AT MURDOCK RENTAL CENTER WAS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL COMPLAINING OF HEADACHES AND SORE THROAT.  BACK TO WORK ON 5-30-91.  MR. MALACISI HAD NO CONTACT WITH SPILL.  ALL DRIVERS AT TERMINAL WILL HAVE A SAFETY MEETING TO DISCUSS THIS CASE AND ERRORS THAT WERE MADE IN HANDLING.  FIRE CHIEF AND HM TEAM FROM SCENE TO BE INVITED TO SAFETY MEETING TO SPEAK TO DRIVERS.  WASTE REMOVAL: WASTE WAS REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM AND WILL BE HAULED OFF BY CHEM CON.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND STATE OF FLORIDA EMERGENCT RESPONSE COMMISSION IN TALLAHASSEE AND CHARLOTTE COUNTY EMERGENCY CENTER CALLED TO REPORT EVACUATION AND VICTIM EXPOSED TO FUMES.  NRC GAVE ASSIGNED REPORT #73747 TO THE INCIDENT.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON 05/30/91 AT APPROXIMATELY 01:36 HOURS, I, KAREN NICHOLS (HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR) OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177, WAS INCIDENT COMMANDER OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT ON OUR FACILITY.  OUR HAZ MAT UNIT WAS DISPATCHED TO A/C 942AX DUE TO A STRONG, INK TYPE ODOR,  AFTER UNLOADING THE AIRCRAFT, THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR WAS DETERMINED TO A PAINT THINNER FROM SINCLAIR VALENTINE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKED IN AN OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WHICH HAD NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON IT.  IT DID HAVE AND ICAO SPECIFICATION ORIENTATION LABEL ON IT (1). THERE WERE NO SHIPPERS CERTIFICATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WITH THIS SHIPMENT.  INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX I FOUND ONE 1-GALLON CAPACITY METAL CAN WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE.  THE CLOSURE HAD NO POSITIVE SECURING MEANS. THE LABEL ON THE METAL CAN (PHOTOCOPIED AND INCLUDED IN THIS REPORT) STATED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS COMBUSTIBLE AND A STRONG EYE IRRITANT.  THERE WERE NO OTHER HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE METAL CAN.  THERE WERE NO ORIENTATION MARKINGS ON THE METAL CAN.  NO DAMAGE WAS NOTICEABLE TO THE METAL CAN OR THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 8 OZ. OF THE PRODUCT SOAKED INTO THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  CAUSE OF THE LEAKAGE WAS DETERMINED TO BE INSUFFICIENT OUTAGE.  THREE OF OUR EMPLOYEES EXPERIENCED HEADACHES FROM THE VAPOR DISPERSION OF THIS PRODUCT.  THE SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUT HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.  IT HAD BEEN REPACKED IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND CERTIFICATION WILL BE OBTAINED FROM THE SHIPPER, UPON WHICH TIME THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED VIA TRUCK.  A COPY OF THE ABX AIR, INC. INCIDENT REPORT ON THE AIRCRAFT INCIDENT ITSELF IS AVAILABLE TO THE FAA AND THE D.O.T. UPON REQUEST.

column168: ON 05/16/91, TRAIN HOKV 16 DERAILED SOUTH OF VANDERBILT, TX.  UNION PACIFIC PERSONNEL (LEO TIERNEY, GEOFF REEDER, BOB STINE AND OTHERS) RESPONDED AND FOUND TANK CAR UTLX 37607 HAD LEFT THE TRACK AND WAS STRUCK BY AN UNKNOWN OBJECT WHICH TORE AWAY A SMALL PORTION OF THE JACKET (APPROXIMATELY 18" IN DIAMETER).  OBJECT ALSO DENTED THE TANK SHELL AND HEAD ON THE A END WHERE THEY WERE WELDED TOGETHER.  NO GOUGING OCCURRED AND NO METAL WAS REMOVED.  HOWEVER, THE WELD BETWEEN THE HEAD AND FIRST RING CRACKED AND ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE (CRACK MEASURED ABOUT 4"). UTLX 36707 WAS LYING WITH THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING TOWARD THE GROUND. ALTHOUGH THE CRACK WAS AT THE 9 O'CLOCK POSITION, THE POINT OF DAMAGE WAS ON THE GROUND.  WATER WAS PUMPED INTO THE CAR TO STOP THE PRODUCT FROM LEAKING.  OTHER RAILCARS WERE REMOVED FROM TANK CAR UTLX 36707 AND CAR WAS ROLLED UPRIGHT AND THE PRODUCT BURNED IN A FLARE OPERATION.  THE CAR WAS THEN FILLED WITH WATER TO FORCE ANY REMAINING NITROGEN.  TANK CAR WAS THEN FILLED WITH NITROGEN AT ATMOSPHERIC PRESSURE AND SENT FOR REPAIR.

column168: ON 05/07/91, TRAIN CREW (ALHO-06) NOTICED THAT TANK CAR CALX 3028 WAS DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE CAP WHEN MOVED.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT (UP AMELIA YARD) AND SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) TOM ROBINSON RESPONDED.  SSA/HM ROBINSON'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED, THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE CAP WAS LOOSE AND THE NOZZLE CAP DID NOT HAVE A GASKET WHICH CAUSED THE LEAK.  SSA/HM ROBINSON CORRECTED THESE DEFICIENCIES AND NOTIFIED TRINITY CHEMICAL COMPANY (TERRY FISHER).

column168: VESSEL STATEMENT: 5/8/91 1000 HRS-CONTAINER NO. SLDU-869689-7 (IMO 6.1) WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKY ON DECK WITH STRONG SMELL AROUND IT.  SPILLAGE WASHED OVERBOARD AND DECK UNDER THE CONTAINER CLEANED.  FREQUENT CHECKS OF THE ABOVE CONTAINER CARRIER OUT - NO FURTHER LEAK OBSERVED BUT STRONG SMELL STILL PERSISTED IN THE VICINITY. MAY 9, 1991 - CONTAINER NO. SLDU 869689-7 (IMO 6.1) CHECKED - NO FURTHER LEAK OBSERVED BUT STRONG SMELL STILL FOUND TO BE PERSISTING IN THE VICINITY. MAY 10, 1991 - 1400 HRS: CONTAINER NO. SLDU 8696897 (IMO 6.1) CHECKED AND NO FURTHER LEAK OBSERVED - STRONG SMELL STILL PERSISTING IN THE VICINITY. 1400 HRS: CONTAINER NO. SLDU - 8696897 LANDED ASHORE (IN SAVANNAH) COPY OF STATEMENT ATTACHED. HAPAG LLOYD STATEMENT: SEE ATTACHED 13 POINT TOO DETAILED TO TYPE WITHIN SPACE PROVIDED. STATEMENT OF FACTS AS THE RELATE TO RECOVERY OF LEAKING DRUMS WITHIN CONTAINER SLDU-869689-7 DISCHARGED UPON VESSEL EMERGENCY REQUEST FROM GULF SPEED V. 1676 ON MAY 10, 1991: 1. EDDIE RAMIREZ WAS CONTACTED BY JACK MCDERMOTT AT ACL ON THRUSDAY, MAY 9TH ADVISING THEY HAD RECEIVED WORD FROM THE VESSEL THAT THERE WAS LEAKAGE AND CONTAINER MIGHT HAVE TO BE DISCHARGED AT SAVANNAH.  THEY WOULD LET US KNOW.  MEANWHILE, EDDIE SENT THE INITIAL MEMO ALERTING EVERYONE. 2. DON WRINKLE OF ALBURY MIAMI CONTACTED MERCATOR SHIPPING (CONSIGNEE) WHO DECLINED ANY RESPONSIBILITY ON THE BASIS THEY HAD NOT TAKEN DELIVERY OF THE CONTAINER.  THIS WAS PASSED ON TO JOHN CARIO.  DON WRINKLE WAS CONTACTED ON MAY 9TH AFTER NOTIFICATION FROM CARIO.  (EARL HUGHES' MEMO OF 5/9/91).  PRIOR TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE BY EDDIE RAMIREZ TO DON WRINKLE TO ADVISE THE CONSIGNEE, ETC., OF WHAT HAD HAPPENED. 3. ACL WAS ADVISED TO NOTIFY CUSTOMS OF THEIR INTENTIONS TO TAKE THE CONTAINER OFF THE VESSEL.  THIS WAS APPARENTLY DONE IMMEDIATELY.  THE CONTAINER WAS IN FACT DISCHARGED TO THE PIER. 4.US COAST GUARD WAS NOT NOTIFIED BY ACL AS PER JACK MCDERMOTT ALL PRECAUTIONS FOR CLEAN-UP HAD BEEN TAKEN AND PERFORMED AT SEA.  EARL HUGHES WAS ADVISED BY JACK MCDERMOTT THAT CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES HAD BEEN PERFORMED AS PER IMCO REQUIREMENTS, USING RAGS AND PLENTY OF WATER.  AFTERWARDS, JACK ADVISED THE RAGS WERE INCINERATED.  ON MONDAY, MAY 13, EARL HUGHES IMMEDIATELY REQUESTED SAME BY TELEPHONE TO JACK MCDERMOTT WHO ADVISED SAME WOULD BE OBTAINED AND PASSED TO US ON THE VESSEL'S OUTWARD CALL AT SAVANNAH.  MEANWHILE, BY MEMO, ASKED JOHN CARIO TO ADVISE ACL IN HOUSTON OF OUR REQUIREMENT AS WELL IN ORDER IT BE PROPERLY AND TIMELY PREPARED FOR US. 5. UPON ARRIVAL OF VESSEL ON MAY 10TH, (FRIDAY) THE CONTAINER DISCHARGES AND WE PROCEEDED TO HANDLE ACCORDINGLY. 6. HAPAG LLOYD WAS ADVISED BY ACL THAT THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN DISCHARGED TO AN ISOLATED AREA BEHIND WAREHOUSE 10 ON THE PIER.  NO VISIBLE LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED BUT AND ODOR WAS PRESENT AT ONE END OF THE CONTAINER.  THIS WAS LATER CONFIRMED BY MR. DAVID PETERSON, INDEPENDENT SURVEYOR APPOINTED DIRECTLY BY PHONE BY A MR. MADER OF MADER TRADING, ANTWERP. 7. M

column168: PACKAGE WAS DELIVERED ON 5/20/91 TO CONTINENTAL WATER.  THEIR EMPLOYEE, (ARRON ELLIS) OPENED THE PACKAGE AND FOUND THE SOLUTION HAD BEEN PLACED IN ANOTHER CARTON.  THE ORIGINAL CARTON WAS DAMP AS WELL AS THE PACKAGING MATERIAL.  ARRON RECEIVED MINOR SKIN IRRITATION.  HE WASHED HIS HANDS WITH WATER WHICH STOPPED THE BURNING. AT THE END OF PAVING WORK SHIFT, ON WEDNESDAY MAY 22, 1991, TROXLER MODEL 4640 WAS BEING TRANSPORTED ON A 1987 FORD VAN AND PACKAGED IN THE SHIPPING BOX PURCHASED FROM TROXLER TO TRANSPORT THE DEVICE BACK TO THE CENTRAL STORAGE FACILITY.  ON RTE. 63 APPROXIMATELY 0.5 MILES NORTH OF RTE. 616 INTERSECTION AND APPROXIMATELY 14.5 MILES S.E. OF FREMONT, VIRGINIA IN A REMOTE AREA IN DICKENSON COUNTY, VIRGINIA, THE VAN CAUGHT FIRE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER AND BY THAT TIME, THE VAN WAS EVACUATED. THIS HAPPENED APPROXIMATELY 7:30 PM.  THE DANTE FIRE DEPARTMENT & DICKENSON COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED.  I WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 8:30 PM.  IT TOOK ME APPROXIMATELY ONE (1) HOUR TO GET TO THE SCENE.  WHEN I ARRIVED THE VAN WAS COMPLETELY BURNED UP.  THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY CORDONED OFF AND I ATTENDED THE SCENE UNTIL 2:00 AM. WHEN EVERYTHING HAD BEEN TESTED AND DEEMED SAFE.  A TEAM OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OFFICERS LED BY JACK R. TOLBERT, JR. FROM THE DEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY SERVICES DROVE FROM WYTHEVILLE, VIRGINIA TO THE SCENE ARRIVING AT APPROXIMATELY MIDNIGHT.  THE GAUGE WAS THEN CHECKED WHILE STILL IN THE VAN, THEN REMOVED AND CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE SAFE AND NOT LEAKING.  AT THIS POINT, I LOADED THE GAUGE AND BROUGHT IT BACK TO OUR STORAGE FACILITY.  THE OUTSIDE OF THE GAUGE WAS BLACKENED AND THE PLASTIC FACE WAS BURNED, BUT THE GAUGE WAS ALL IN TACK AND THE SHIELD WAS STILL IN PLACE.  A LEAK TEST WAS SENT TO TROXLER LABORATORIES TO INSURE SAFETY BEFORE THE GAUGE IS TO BE SENT BACK TO TROXLER.  THE LEAK TEST REPORT CAME BACK NORMAL.  THE FOLLOWING WERE NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT: DANTE, VIRGINIA FIRE DEPARTMENT DICKENSON COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TROXLER ELECTRONICS USDOT NUCLEAR REGULATORY COMMISSION VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF EMERGENCY SERVICES

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER GOING EAST ON I-40 JUST PASSED THE NEWPORT, TN. EXIT, THE HIGHWAY STARTS TO CURVE TO THE RIGHT, OUR DRIVER SAID HE WAS THINKING ABOUT THE POSSIBILITY OF FOG HE MIGHT ENCOUNTER WHEN HE CROSSED THE N.C. STATE LINE AND WAS NOT PROPERLY WATCHING THE ROADWAY.  HE RAN OFF THE ROAD INTO THE MEDIUM, LOSS CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE, OVERTURNED, SKIDDED DOWN THE MEDIUM BEFORE COMING TO REST IN THE CENTER OF THE MEDIUM.  THE FRONT COMPARTMENT #1 PUNCTURED, #2 THE MANHOLE COVER VENT BROKE OFF, #3 STAYED INTACT AND #4 REAR COMPARTMENT PUNCTURED SPILLING APPROX, 7000 GAL. OF AVIATION GASOLINE.  THE NEWPORT FIRE DEPT. FOAMED DOWN THE TRUCK, TANK AND THE ACCIDENT AREA. THE ACCIDENT WAS INVESTIGATED BY THE TN. HIGHWAY PATROL, TN. PSC, TN. EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT DIV., A MR. JOHN WEST & BILL FERGUSON OF THE DIV. OF WATER & POLLUTION CONTROL, MR. CHUCH EGER USEPA REGION 4, WOOTEN PERSONNEL, INSURANCE CLAIMS REP., AND HARTSELL WRECKER SER. THE CLEAN-UP OPERATION IS BEING CONDUCTED BY FERGUSON HARBOR SER. INC. DIRECTED BY MR. MIKE MOODY, JOHNSON CITY OFFICE (615) 477-4995.

DRUM WAS LOADED IN BAR OF TRAILER BY THE BACK DOOR AND HAD BEEN BLOCKED WITH OTHER FREIGHT ON TRUCK.  UPON ARRIVAL A VAPOR ODOR WAS NOTICED WHEN THE BACK DOORS OF TRAILER WERE OPENED.  THE FREIGHT THAT WAS USED FOR BLOCKING HAD SHIFTED, ENROUTE, & HAD ALLOWED DRUM TO TURN ON IT'S SIDE. DRUM WAS CHECKED FOR DAMAGE.  IT HAD BEEN DENTED ON ONE SIDE & HAD A SMALL CRACK IN THE UPPER PORTION OF THE DENTED SIDE OF APPROXIMATELY 1/2 INCH IN LENGTH.  THE CITY OF KENNER FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED & DISPATCHED A UNIT TO ASSIST.  THEY ALSO WASHED DOWN THE AREA IN TRAILER WHICH HAD BEEN AFFECTED.  EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBER ON SHIPPERS DECLARATION WAS CALLED. SUSAN TRACY WITH CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED ON THIS PHONE CALL, WHO IN TURN, NOTIFIED MR. STEVE BEARMAN WITH SHIPPER.  HE CALLED US BACK & ADVISED US OF HAZARDOUS PROPERTIES OF THIS MATERIAL & OF PROPER WAY TO HANDLE.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: ON 05/17/91, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) ROBERT FORDEMWALT WAS NOTIFIED THAT CONTAINER ESAU 36, ON FLATCAR TTWX 982387, WAS LEAKING.  SSA/HM FORDEMWALT RESPONDED AND TRANSPORTATION MANAGER, ENVIROSAFE SERVICES OF IDAHO (KEM WALL) WAS ON THE SCENE.  INSPECTION OF RAIL BIN DETERMINED A FAILED WELD SEAM AND SOLID PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE CRACK.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED FROM THE DECK OF FLATCAR AND GROUND AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED BY APPLYING A LIQUID FOAM MATERIAL AROUND THE FAILED SEAM.  RAIL BIN WAS MOVED VIA TRUCK TO ENVIROSAFE, GRAND VIEW, IDAHO FOR PROCESSING AND REPAIR. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND IDAHO HAZARDOUS WASTE COMPLIANCE OFFICER WERE NOTIFIED.

SA/HM JARA RESPONDED AND MET WITH STOCKTON FIRE CAPTAIN (M. SIBLER). SA/HM JARA'S AND CAPTAIN SIBLER'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE TANK CAR HAD TWO COMPARTMENTS.  COMPARTMENT A CONTAINED ISOPROPANOL AND COMPARTMENT B CONTAINED METHYL ETHYL KETONE.  SA/HM JARA'S INSPECTION ALSO DETERMINED THT TANK CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVES.  SA/HM JARA REMOVED SEAL (KCS N-474618) AND APPLIED PRESSURE TO VALVE ROD END ON COMPARTMENT A.  ROD TURNED ABOUT 1/8 INCH AND STOPPED LEAK, STUFFING BOX COVER WAS RESECURED (UP SEAL W-110182). SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) CLIFF HILL WAS NOTIFIED (BY AGENT FOR D.Q.&E.) THAT TANK CAR GATX 85272 CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROSULFIDE WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF CAR AT PERKINS, ARKANSAS. SSA/HM HILL RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PACKING GLAND ON THE TOP OPERATED/BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HAD NO PACKING WHICH ALLOWED LIQUID TO LEAK BETWEEN ROD AND ROD-HOLDER ON THE TOP OF THE CAR.  GLAND WAS REPACKED, PACKING GLAND NUT WAS TIGHTENED WHICH SECURED ROAD AND STOPPED LEAK.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE (CLINT LUNSFORD) WERE ADVISED OF INCIDENT.

column168: SENIOR SPRCIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) CLIFF HILL WAS NOTIFIED BY TRAIN MANAGEMENT, OMAHA, ADVISING TANK CAR TILX 100024 (ON LOCAL GOING TO HOPE FROM PERKINS) HAD ACID LEAKING FROM TOP.  SSA/HM HILL ADVISED TO SET CAR OUT FOR REPAIRS. SSA/HM HILL RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERLINED THAT 10 INCH FILL HOLE HAD THE GASKET OUT OF LINE ALLOWING ACID TO SPILL FROM THE FILL HOLE WHEN CAR MOVED.  GASKET WAS REPLACED WITH GORTEX GASKET SEAL WHICH SECURED CAR. CAR WAS OBSERVED BY SSA/HM HILL WHILE CAR WAS BEING HANDLED FOLLOWING REPAIRS, NO LEAKS WERE NOTED. CHEMTREC NOTIFIED.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE (TONY LANE) WAS ALSO ADVISED OF INCIDENT WITH CAR AND HE ADVISED HE WOULD CONTACT BARTLESVILLE, OK.

SSA/HM ROBINSON RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A FAILED RUPTURE DISC (BS&B, 100 PSI) IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY (THERE WAS NO SECURITY SEAL ON SAFETY VENT COVER/ASSEMBLY). CHEMTREC, LION OIL (CLINT LUNDSFORD), AND LOUISIANA STATE POLICE WRE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2010 HOURS, TUESDAY, MAY 14, 1991, EMPLOYEES AT THE ELKHART, INDIANA CONRAIL YARD OBBSERVED A STEADY VENTING OF PRODUCT.  THE VALVE BOX AREA OF TANK CAR ARIX-3006 (ARGON, REFRIGERATED LIQUID).  TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM AIRCO (R. VISSANT) RESPONDED TO THE LOCATION OF THE TANK CAR AND UPON INSPECTION FOUND THAT VENTING HAS STOPPED AND NO APPARENT MECHANICAL PROBLEM.  MR. VISSANT SURMISED THAT THE TANK CAR'S SAFETY VENT HAD ACTIVATED AND THEN FROZE IN AN OPEN POSITION ALLOWING PRODUCT TO CONTINOUSLY ESCAPE. column168: AT 0325 SORT SUPERVISOR KATHY KASSINOS REPORTED AN ODOR COMING FROM A BOX IN THE MAIN SORT.  CERT 4, TONY FRYE, AND CERT 8, NEAL VAN SAUN, TRIED TO LOCATED THE PACKAGE.  WE FOUND THE PACKAGE INSIDE A CARGO CONTAINER.  WE REMOVED THE PACKAGE AND BROUGHT IT TO THE HAZMAT SORT AREA.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION WE FOUND INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD PACKAGE A ONE-GALLON METAL CONTAINER.  INSIDE THIS METAL CONTAINER WAS A PAINT RELATED MATERIAL. THIS WAS A FRICTION TYPE CONTAINER WITH NO MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE. APPROXIMATELY HALF OF THE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT.  ON THE LABEL OF THE INNER METAL CONTAINER WAS "FLAMMABLE LIQUID".  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT TO INDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS IN THE SECURITY CAGE AT THE HAZMAT SORT BUILDING UNDER LOCK AND KEY.

column168: SPOKE WITH BEN TAYLOR REGARDING RQUAN CCAP INFO ON 8/7/91.  HE STATED ONLY ONE COMMODITY HAD BEEN SPILLED BUT COULD NOT IDENTIFY WHICH OF THE THREE SINCE THERE WERE NO LABELS OR MARKINGS ON BOTTLES - ETHYL ALCOHOL WAS CODED AS THE COMMODITY HAVING BEEN SPILLED.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE OFFICE AND CHECKING EMERGENCY EQUIPMENT, TRIED TO CONTACT DUNKEL AT THE TELEPHONE NUMBER MENTIONED ABOVE.  INSTEAD, DISPATCHER CONNECTED ME WITH BILL PITTSER, NUCLEAR MEDICINE TECHNOLOGIST FOR OIL CITY AREA MEDICAL CENTER.  PITTSER MENTIONED THAT THE CARRIER WAS TRANSPORTING MOLYBDENUM GENERATORS WHEN A TIRE BLEW OUT AND THE VEHICLE RAN INTO A LAMPPOST.  ONE GENRATOR BOX WAS PUNCTURED AND HAZMAT TEAMS GOT A READING OF APPROXIMATELY 300 MILLIROENTGENS PER HOUR FROM ONE BOX.  THEY ARE OF COURSE CONCERNED ABOUT THIS, AND WANT TO KNOW WHAT TO DO ABOUT CLEANING UP OR HANDLING THE SITUATION.  GOT DIRECTIONS FROM PITTSER AS TO THE EXACT LOCATION OF THE ACCIDENT: CENTER STREET IN OIL CITY.  FOLLOW ROUTE 8 TO OIL CITY AND CROSS THE SECOND BRIDGE.  CENTER STREET IS THAT STREET, AND IT WILL BE RIGHT IN FRONT OF YOU. ARRIVED ON SCENE APPROXIMATELY 9:30 AM MAY 24.  AFTER INTRODUCING MYSELF TO THE LOCAL RESPONDERS (POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL), DID A QUICK SURVEY OF THE PACKAGES INVOLVED.  THE VEHICLE, A MINIVAN, HAD JUST BEEN TOWED FROM THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  ONE BLOCK OF CENTER STREET IN OIL CITY (BETWEEN SENECA AND ELM STREETS) HAD BEEN CORDONED OFF, PRIMARILY WITH THE TRAFFIC CONES.  THE RIGHT LANE OF CENTER STREET NORTHBOUND (ON THE EAST SIDE) WAS ALSO STRUNG WITH YELLOW TAPE AS A BOUNDARY LINE. LOCATED ON THE SIDEWALK WERE TWO LARGE BLACK POLYETHYLENE BAGS AND APPROXIMATELY 15 TO 20 FEET AWAY TO THE NORTH FROM THESE WERE THREE OTHER PLASTIC BLACK BAGS.  JUST BEYOND THIS WAS AN ORANGE TARPAULIN AND ON THIS TARPULIN WERE SOME "KIDDY POOLS".

column168: ON MAY 28, 1991, ABOUT 10:00 AM, HAPAG LLOYD WAS CONTACTED BY THE PORT CAPTAIN (HOUSTON) THAT CONTAINER HLCU-436655-0 CONTAINED A TOXIC CHEMICAL AND WAS LEAKING, U.S. COAST GUARD HELD VESSEL AT ANCHOR UNTIL OHM RECOVERY TEAM ARRIVED ON BOARD AND PROPER CLEAN-UP WAS PERFORMED.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS RE-PACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND AFOREMENTIONED CLEAN-UP OPERATION PERFORMED.  THE VESSEL WAS THEN ALLOWED TO ENTER THE PORT FOR DOCKING. THE CONTAINER WAS DISCHARGED TO THE PIER FOR FURTHER DE-CONTAMINATION CLEAN-UP AND LAB SAMPLES TAKEN AT U.S. COAST GUARD REQUEST.  TEST RESULTS HAVE NOW BEEN RECEIVED.  SHIPMEMT IS PENDING A FURTHER INVESTIGATION AS TO WHAT MUST BE DONE FROM THIS POINT.  AT THE TIME OF THIS FILING, THE CARGO REMAINS ON THE PIER AT GEORGIA PORTS AUTHORITY, GARDEN CITY TERMINALS. HAPAG LLOYD, NEW YORK IS PRESENTLY FINALIZING RESULTS WITH THE SHIPPER.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: ON MAY 29, 1991, ENVIRITE'S DRIVER EDWARD PERALTA WAS PRESENT AS AN LTV EMPLOYEE GRAVITY LOADED 4,970 GALLONS OF WASTE PRODUCT INTO A TANKER VIA THE CENTER MANWAY.  ENVIRITE'S DRIVER SIGNALLED THE LTV EMPLOYEE TO CLOSE THE VALVE FORM THE STORAGE TANK AS HE APPROACHED FULL LADING.  AS THE LTV EMPLOYEE TRIED TO CLOSE THE VALVE,  THE STEM BROKE OFF WITHOUT FULLY CLOSING, THUS LEAVING A TRICKLE OF WASTE FLOWING INTO THE TANKER.  THE LTV EMPLOYEE INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO REMOVE THE LOADING HOSE FROM THE TANKER'S CENTER MANWAY.  THE LTV EMPLOYEE THEN PULLED A REMOVAL ROP WHICH RETRACTED THE HOSE RELEASED TO ITS STORAGE POSITION.  DURING THE PROCESS, THE HOSE RELEASED THE WASTE IN QUESTION.  NO WASTE WAS LOST FROM THE TANKER, OR AS A RESULT OF THE FAILURE OF ANY OF THE VESSEL'S APPURTENANCES.  THE RELEASED WASTE WAS DEPOSTED WITHIN A GRAVEL LINES CATCH BASIN AT LTV'S LOADING SITE.  LTV IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP THE ARE, PACKAGING THE MATERIAL THE STORAGE UNTIL PROPER PERMITS ARE VERIFIED OR SECURED.  NO ONE WAS EITHER HOSPITALIZED OR INJURED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  A DRIVER DEBRIEFING AND SITE VISIT WERE CONDUCTED BY ENVIRITE'S OPERATIONS MANAGER AND ASSISTANT OPERATIONS MANAGER.

CAR WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED LOCATION WHERE WATER IS AVAILABLE, IF NEEDED.  FMC WAS NOTIFIED AND THE FMC PHOSPHOROUS TEAM RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. FMC PHOSPHOROUS TEAM'S INSPECTION DETERMINED A DEFECTIVE GASKET AROUND THE MANWAY COVER WHICH ALLOWED SMALL AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE.  FMC TEAM MADE TEMPORARY REPAIR ENABLING THE CAR TO BE MOVED TO THE PLANT FOR PERMANENT REPAIR. CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE PLANT, REPAIR COMPLETED AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.
